<div class="s2"><h1>Computer Viruses: Myth or Reality?</h1><p><a href="/lib/?lang=en&amp;author=Israel%2C%20Howard">Howard Israel</a><br/> <em>National Computer Security Conference Proceedings (10th): Computer Security - From Principles to Practices, 21-24 September 1987, pp.226-230</em><br/> <em>September 1987</em></p><script type="text/rocketscript">var disqus_url = 'http://vxheaven.org/lib/ahi00.html';</script><div class="ci"><a href="/lib/?ci=ahi00">2</a></div>[<a style="" href="/lib/?lang=EN&amp;index=TH#ahi00">Back to index</a>] [<a href="/lib/ahi00.html#disqus_thread">Comments</a>]<br/><h2>Abstract</h2><p>This paper will show that a computer virus [COHEN] may be no more a threat to computer systems than a Trojan Horse and any protection mechanism that will work against a a Trojan Horse will also work against against computer virus, specifically a mandatory policy (e.g. [BELL/LAP] [BIBA]) In addition, it will discuss two possible protection mechanissms that address the Trojan Horse threat.</p><p>[<a href="/lib/ahi00.html">Read the article</a>]</p></div>
